aThis volume explores practices and experiences in Chinese popular religion. The research adds new materials and new approaches to well-known worships such as the cults of doomsday, underworld, and Lord Guan on the one hand, and draws attention to under-the-radar deities and holy figures hiding in the mountainous countryside or among the urban crowd. While this book centers on Chinese popular religion, it will be of use to non-China scholars in folklore, religious art, and ritual studies as well as China scholars in popular culture from late-medieval to contemporary times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReligion and sociologyzChina. 4aAsian Studies. 4aContemporary Society. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aReligion and Theology. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aChinese religion in practice, popular religion, visual text, oral text, text.1 aCao, Sherry Xinyi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCao, Xinyi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChao, Shin-yi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChao, Shin-yi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChau, Adam Yuet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Yongchao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChien-chuan, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFan, Chun-wu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoossaert, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHo, Eunice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHou, Chong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Shih-wei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g